ces of marginalized communities, particularly African American women, whose perspectives and labor have been consistently overlooked. Toxic Water, Toxic System offers a fresh perspective on the ties between urban austerity policies, environmental harm, and the advancement of white supremacist agendas in predominantly Black and brown cities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aEnvironmental justicezMichiganzDetroity21st century. 0aLiability for water pollution damageszMichiganzDetroity21st century. 0aWater rightszMichiganzDetroity21st century. 0aWaterxPollutionxLaw and legislationzMichiganzDetroity21st century. 0aWater-supplyxGovernment policyzMichiganzDetroity21st century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Activism & Social Justice.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311079135840uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520975217?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520975217423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520975217/original  a978-3-11-079135-8  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles